`crates/steno/src/bin` is a set of independent CLI entry points, each compiling `dict.steno` (or `dict.infinite.steno`) via the `steno` lib crate into a distinct downstream artifact: Plover JSON dictionaries (`build_dict.rs`), Neovim snippet files (`build_nvim.rs`), javelin-ext C++ headers (`build_javelin.rs`), a manual size-comparison report (`measure.rs`), and a visualization JSON tree (`viz_data/`). Depending on this directory means running one of these binaries to regenerate a specific artifact; none of them import from each other, and none expose a library surface — all real logic lives in the `steno` crate.

All four flat-file binaries share the same structural pattern and the same trap: `root()` hardcodes the workspace root as `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR/../..`, assuming the binary sits two directories below the workspace root where `dict.steno` and `out/` live — moving any of these crates breaks that path in all of them independently (no shared helper, so each must be fixed separately). They also share the collision-guard-before-write convention: `build_dict.rs` and `build_nvim.rs` both check for stroke/keyset collisions via `guard()` and refuse to write *any* output file if either profile collides, using `BTreeSet` dedup for collision reporting. `measure.rs` performs the same dedup for its own reporting but writes nothing. Errors are stringly-typed (`Result<_, String>`) across all four, funneled to a `fail()`/`main()` pair that prints to stderr and returns `ExitCode::FAILURE` without panicking on expected failure paths.

`build_dict.rs` and `build_nvim.rs` both call `expand_dict(&entries, None)` (no profile filter) and then derive multiple output shapes from the same expanded list — a change to `expand_dict`'s signature or the meaning of `None` affects both. `measure.rs` depends on the broadest slice of the `steno` public API and will break first on any lib signature change. `build_javelin.rs` is the outlier: it consumes a different source file (`dict.infinite.steno`) and skips the expensive Pass B enumeration entirely, making it structurally unlike the other three.

`viz_data/` is self-contained with its own two-pass pipeline and JSON output; see its own rollup for internal coupling.